      <tr><td colspan=1  style='font-size: 9.5px;'>12 threads, <a href=journal.html?user=10704&start=0>1</a>  page(s) long</td><td  style='font-size: 9.5px;' align=right>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></form><ul><table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100342800794350></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100342800794350><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=10704&mid=100342800794350>DAY ONE CONCLUSION</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=10704&mid=100342800794350#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=10704><span id=Scholar>The One and Only JanaLaser</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>22 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Oct 18th 2:00 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.73]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I was hopelessly inept at firing my other spell. I could feel the power, a drawing in of coldest air, transformed by my inherent power into a minor ice cloud that could be settled on a target, flow into and then from my fingers. <br><br>I would get the intial stages of casting accomplished and Guardian Aron or one of the other Guards would have already taken care of the bandit. I never really saw a complete cast of the spell. In all honesty, I was terrified. I was sure I was not going to survive the encounter, but it was over in a matter of moments. I was in one piece, and exhilerated, even if I was really only a bystander.<br><br>The guardians went on their way and Aron thanked me for my support, adding "You need to head into the forest at hand here and practice, not only your magical talents but also how to determine which targets to choose, how to handle a weapon, even how to run if need be. You need to start forming your own hunting and killing style, determine when to cast and when to hit, and when to protect yourself. Your mind must be a sponge now, if you are ever to aide in the defense of this land, let alone fight in incursions into the pagan lands. Off with you! The night is at hand, and you must hunt your dinner, find a place to rest and think of all that has happened this day."<br><br>I ran from the river, back to near the towering wall of the Association. Light was coming from the ramparts and from a nearby gathering of stones. I could not see the source of the light near the circle of stones and so I went to investigate, perhaps it was someone else's magical abilities? I reached the stones and saw that the glow was coming from a carving of a dragon on largest of the stones. There was writing on another stone. I had the ability to read apparently. It mentioned the ability to bind myself here and return by releasing my will, whatever that meant. <br><br>The thought struck me that I was becoming insensitive to the wonders and mystery of the day. I was taking what skills and knowledges I had for granted. I was no longer asking myself from whence they had come. It was as if I had settled into an acceptance of the challenges awaiting me, some inner core was hardening with resolve. I wanted the answers, to who and how and why. Where and when were resolved, but the rest would have to wait. I would have to make my way patiently... accepting whatever gifts, whatever companionship, whatever knowledge was granted me by the Ghods or a God. I did not have a clear grasp of that. <br><br>I was feeling chill. The night was falling faster. I caused my magical torch to be lit and felt hunger for the first time. I needed to hunt something that the merchant would buy from me, something to make a few more copper so that I might buy the simple cloak that the merchant had for sale. I headed to an area where I could see others who looked to be in similar circumstances. They were hunting a variety of small creatures and placing items from the kills in the rather roomy backpacks they carried. The thought of the backpack caused me to acquire one. Truly, a magical time and land. <br><br>I noticed a dappled lynx cub nearby and knew I had my first real target. I shielded myself, made sure my stick was ready in my hand and let fly the ice cloud spell. That caught its attention. I let the spell go again, and again, a complete rush of power flinging with each cast! It was injured, but still it came, determined to put one of us out of it's misery. It reached me and I beat it back unmercifully with the stick. I was more animal then it was at this point. At last, it was finished. I took what was edible and what was sellable, thanked my luck and headed back to the Association. <br><br>I sold the skin, bought a plain grey woolen cloak to wrap around myself and then found a common area where a large pot was holding what looked to be a stew of some kind. I asked about joining and was told to take my meat to the spit, draw some ale for myself and partake of the fellowship. The smell was enough to make me ravenous. The people were quiet but friendly. Some said hello, others just nodded. I found a bowl, a spot, some bread and sitting on my new cloak, ate and watched and listened and prepared to go back out into the forest for some night kills. The very good ale however, went to my head. I laid down in my spot, my head on the overturned bowl, spread my cloak around me, and fell into a much needed rest.<br>&nbsp;<br>Nolarita Aurelius, <br>of DAoC, EQ, UO, and finest of all..Legends of Kesmai </td></tr>
