<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100198709513893></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100198709513893><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=10704&mid=100198709513893>RE: Ok, I'll bite</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=10704&mid=100198709513893#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=8887><span id=Scholar>Tindarl</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>35 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Oct 1st 9:44 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I have been looking at various web sites for Camelot information. The people have been just as creative in their web designs for this game as for Everquest. A nice bit of hope that shows people are excited about it.<br><br>In my searches I have noticed many things that I like:<br><br>1) Crafting. The recepies are not secrets, a part that is desired to be produced has it's components listed on the screen and the player just needs to go fetch them. No more CTRL-clicking stacks of random parts to see if anyting happens. This is not true anymore for EQ since many sites have recepies, but for the player that doesn't have binders full of printed info next to the keyboard (no joke, I know many that do this) it is very convienent.<br><br>Also, failure does not always result in complete loss of components. For a completely new character that is starting out untwinked, this gets very expensive in EQ. My poor SK is doing fletching and tailoring, and soon will be getting spells, he will be always broke.<br><br>2) Quests. This ties in with crafting too. Some quests are not of a kill-loot-turn in type of system. After a period of time you can make a few swords, some guards need them in an outpost, when you turn them in a battle ensues that you help out in. Not sure if this is exactly correct, but you get the idea.<br><br>3) PvP done right. I do not like PvP in EQ. It feels personal and vindictive, more useless than in Quake. In Camelot the character names are removed and replaced with "Invader" or some such tag. And there is a PvP point system that will eventually enhance some skills at certain levels. Very nice touch.<br><br>There are also raids and seiges. A castle can be stormed and conquered to add to your realm, artifacts can be stolen from one realm and taken to another to enhance yours and debuff the others. There is a reason for raids and PvP, not just the adolesent joy of ruining a person's day because that person's post on a message board made you mad.<br><br>4) Twinking. None! WooHoo! If the armor you have is too good for your level, then it rots away. No more level 1 rangers running around in full ivy. Also the game tells you when your armor is too poor for you. It /cons a color just like creatures do and so at a certain point you need to get better.<br><br>There seems to be some drawbacks too, don't get me wrong.<br><br>1) The game feels small. About the size of Antonica for each realm. As fas as I can see, there is no comparison of size to size, but it just feels tiny. It seems easy for the developers to add in areas however. Recently new dungeons have been added. More are surely to come.<br><br>2) Spells. Spells seem limited to "Fireball 1", "Fireball 2", etc. No creative names exist yet. How about "Minor Meteor", then "Meteor", eventually working up to "Merlin's Meteor Shower". This may change with the public release, we can hope. Creative names aren't much, but they make for feelings of accomplishment when upgrading to new spells.<br><br>The choice seems very limited too. Not many "fun spells" like "Dance of the Firefly", "Gaze", or "Eye of Zomm". All battle spells all the time.<br><br>3) Stat enhances. There is an official message board out there, not sure of the address right now, will have to find it and post it. The developers state that stats like strength cannot be enhanced with gear. What you get at the beginning is all you have. Not a good move for those people coming from EQ where a pair of +STR rings is treasure to a warrior or INT/CHA combo for an enchanter. Many will be diassapointed and could be a major reason why some will come, play and go back to EQ.<br><br>Some parts are neither good nor bad, depending on who looks at them.<br><br>1) Combat maneuvers. There are many special attacks that certain classes can perform. Some can use a spear to do direct damage and bleeding, others can use their shield to knock the opponent silly (similar to the SK bash). Combinations of attacks and defensive stances enhance combat to a new level. But for these to work you need to hit 2 or 3 times in a row, without missing. Howm any triple hits do you get in EQ? I looked, not often enough. Even with dual weild and double attack.<br><br>2) Capes and other armor. People have been wanting cape animation for EQ for quite a while. I have not been for or against it. Make it like the Velious armors so it can be turned off for those with slower connections of systems. Camelot has flowing capes. Can a creature reach out and grab it as you run away so it can stop you? If so, many will scream about it as being an unfair advantage.<br><br>And almost any armor can be dyed colors. Nice for magic users that can make cloth look like leather so in PvP they aren't the primary targets. Until they start the arm waving and lightning bolts come lashing out of their fingers. Then they have a problem. heh<br><br>Holy Crap this has gotten long. More at a later time perhaps.<br><br>Tindarl Wolfhugger<br>Warriors of Living Force<br>Seventh Hammer Server<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
